Someone please correct me if I&#x27;m wrong, but I guess the shortcut is something like this:<p><pre><code>  Z = X[1] * X[2] * X[3] * ... * X[n];
  for i in (1..n-1) {
    Z = Z/X[i];
    g = GCD(X[i], Z); 
    if (g > 1) {
      // check each other key to see which have g as a factor
      for j in (j+1..n) {
        if (X[j] % g == 0) {
          log that keys i & j have g as a common factor;
        }
     }
  }
</code></pre>
Rather than having to run the inner loop for every iteration of the outer loop, it only has to run in the case where there is a common factor.<p>For instance, to check for common factors in [4, 13, 10] we initially compute Z = 4 * 13 * 10 = 520. Then we start with the first key, 4. Divide Z by 4 yielding 130. Do 4 and 130 have a common factor? gcd(4,130) = 2, so yes they do. We now check each remaining key individually (13 & 10) for divisibility by 2 and report which one(s) match, (in this case, 10). Then we continue with the second key, 13. Divide Z by 13 yielding 10. Do 13 & 10 have a common factor? No, they don&#x27;t, and there are no more keys left to check, so we&#x27;re done.
